## Example 3 — Describe Center and Spread Using a Box Plot

Describe the center and spread of a data set using either the mean and standard deviation or the five-number summary. Justify the choice by constructing a box plot.

### Step 1: Construct a Box Plot

Create a box plot from the data to visualize the spread and identify any outliers.

### Step 2: Determine the Shape

Use the box plot to assess symmetry. A symmetric distribution has the median roughly centered in the box and whiskers of similar length. Skewed distributions have a longer whisker on one side and the median closer to one end of the box.

### Step 3: Choose and Calculate Statistics

* If the box plot shows symmetry, use the mean and standard deviation
* If the box plot shows skewness or outliers, use the five-number summary

Representative data set:
[
47, 16, 70, 80, 28, 33, 91, 55, 60, 45, 86, 54, 30, 98, 34, 87, 44, 35,
64, 58, 27, 67, 72, 68, 31, 95, 37, 41, 97, 56, 49, 71, 84, 66, 45, 93
]

## Example 4 — Analyze Outliers and Their Effects

In real-world contexts, identify outliers in a data set, construct a box plot, calculate appropriate statistics, and describe how the outlier affects the measures of center and spread.

### Step 1: Identify Potential Outliers

Examine the data for values that are substantially different from the rest. For example, in a data set of daily exercise minutes, a value of 10 minutes might be an outlier if most values cluster around 55–62 minutes.

### Step 2: Construct a Box Plot

Create a box plot to confirm the presence of outliers visually.

### Step 3: Calculate Statistics With and Without the Outlier

Calculate appropriate measures of center and spread for the full data set. Then remove the outlier and recalculate to compare.

### Step 4: Describe the Effect

Explain how the outlier influences the mean, median, standard deviation, or range. Outliers typically have a larger effect on the mean and standard deviation than on the median and IQR.

Representative contexts:

* Flight prices from Los Angeles to New York:
[
182, 234, 264, 271, 277, 314, 317, 455
]

* Exercise minutes tracked over 10 days:
[
57, 60, 53, 59, 57, 61, 61, 54, 62, 10
]

## Mixed Exercises

The mixed exercises provide practice across all skills from this lesson. Problems include:

* Constructing histograms and box plots for raw data sets and describing distribution shape
* Selecting and justifying appropriate measures of center and spread for symmetric versus skewed data
* Working with contextual data sets involving outliers and analyzing their effect on statistics
* Comparing two data sets or distributions using statistical summaries and graphical displays
* Removing outliers from a data set, reconstructing the box plot, and comparing means and medians before and after
* Matching histograms to their corresponding box plots
* Interpreting real-world data presented in tables and graphs
* Researching and defining distribution types such as bimodal distributions
* Creating examples of symmetric and non-symmetric real-world data
* Explaining why the mean and standard deviation are used for symmetric distributions while the five-number summary is preferred for skewed distributions

Some problems present data in tables or graphs that require reading values before analysis.

